SLUG: healthstack-patient-portal

# Startup brief: HealthStack Patient Portal (US healthcare MVP, Next.js + Supabase + Stripe)

Note on slugs: run artifacts for this job live in the existing run directory
`upwork-runs/for-this-make-sure-to/` (already created by the graph). The
PUBLIC-FACING demo slug that the demo-builder must use everywhere it matters is
`healthstack-patient-portal`: the demo folder
`../michaelwegter.com/public/demos/healthstack-patient-portal/`, the `slug` field
in `src/data/workSamples.js`, and the live route
`/work-samples/healthstack-patient-portal`. Use `healthstack-patient-portal` for
anything a visitor or URL sees; keep run-time intermediates in the existing run dir.

## What the client actually wants
An early-stage startup is building a US-market healthcare web app and needs a
full-stack developer to build the first real working version "properly." The
named stack is non-negotiable: Next.js, Supabase, Stripe, Vercel, TypeScript.
The product surface they describe: user accounts, payments/subscriptions,
patient + admin dashboards, role-based secure access, careful handling of
sensitive healthcare data, and a clean simple UX. They point at
https://sesamecare.com/ for style/flow (a consumer-friendly care marketplace:
browse/book care, pay per visit or via membership) but stress it is a reference,
not a clone. The deeper ask is trust and judgment: they want someone who
understands that privacy, permissions, security, and HIPAA-aware development
matter from day one, who gives realistic estimates, communicates well, and can
help a non-technical founding team make sensible early architecture decisions.
This is as much a "can I trust this person to build it right" hire as a coding
hire.

## HARD GATE: the application keyword
The posting says: "Proposals that do not start with HEALTHSTACK may not be
reviewed." The cover letter MUST begin with the literal word HEALTHSTACK as its
very first token (e.g. "HEALTHSTACK -" or "HEALTHSTACK." on line one). This is a
pass/fail filter on the client side. intake MUST capture this as an explicit
requirement; proposal-writer MUST honor it; evaluator MUST verify the cover
letter's first word is HEALTHSTACK before anything else. Do not bury it, do not
paraphrase it.

## Recommended demo direction (lean full)
Build a working "HealthStack" patient portal demo that proves the exact stack and
the exact concerns the client lists. The single most impressive thing to show:
role-gated login (patient vs admin/clinician) leading into an appointment booking
flow that ends in a Stripe-style checkout, with a patient dashboard and a separate
admin dashboard that demonstrably sees different data. The flow mirrors the Sesame
reference (find care -> pick a time -> pay) while foregrounding the security story.

Hero flow (the thing media-capture records):
  1. Log in as a patient (seeded demo account).
  2. Browse a small set of services/providers, pick an appointment slot
     (booking/scheduling = a stated "nice to have" and a Sesame-style core flow).
  3. Confirm + pay via a mocked Stripe checkout (payment intent / subscription
     style), land on a confirmation with the booking in the patient dashboard.
  4. Show that switching to the admin account reveals an admin dashboard with the
     booking + a different, permission-scoped data view, demonstrating role-based
     access (this is the Supabase RLS / "secure access for different user types"
     story made visible).

Weave the HIPAA-aware framing through the UI so it reads as deliberate, not
decorative: a visible "PHI minimized" note, an access/audit-log panel showing who
viewed what, and a secure-file-upload affordance for a medical form (another
stated nice-to-have). These are cheap to show and directly answer "handling
healthcare-related user data carefully."

## Demo hosting + backend (greenlit)
Per CLAUDE.md the demo is a same-origin static app under
`michaelwegter.com/public/demos/<slug>/`, NOT a deployed Next.js server. That is
fine and should be stated plainly in the proposal: the live demo is a faithful
front-end + a real mw-backend standing in for Supabase/Stripe, and the production
build for the client would be Next.js on Vercel with Supabase Auth/Postgres/RLS
and real Stripe webhooks. Do not try to run an actual Next.js/Supabase/Vercel
deployment in this workflow.

Backend: GREENLIT. Add a `healthstack_blueprint.py` to mw-backend by cloning the
`spotify_blueprint.py` structure (do NOT touch auth core, the DB schema, or
existing blueprints beyond registering the new one). It should expose:
  - mock JWT auth with TWO seeded roles: a patient account and an admin account
    (mirror the existing JWT pattern; this stands in for Supabase Auth + RLS).
  - appointment/slot data + a "book" endpoint that records a booking against the
    logged-in user.
  - a mock Stripe payment/checkout endpoint that returns a fake confirmed
    payment/subscription (NO real Stripe keys, NO real charges).
  - role-scoped reads: the patient endpoint returns only that patient's data; the
    admin endpoint returns the aggregate/admin view. Make the role separation real
    in the API, not faked in the front end, so it genuinely demonstrates
    server-enforced permissions (the RLS analogue).
Seed and RECORD the demo credentials (patient + admin) so deploy-test can log in
and so the cover letter/deck can invite the client to try both roles.

## Prototype-vs-full decision
Lean FULL. None of the three fallback triggers fire: the hero (auth ->
book -> pay -> role-scoped dashboards) is fully buildable with mw-backend mocks
inside budget, it fits the file/time caps, and the concept is interactive, not a
throwaway mockup. Real Stripe charges, a real Supabase project, real Vercel
deploy, and actual HIPAA certification are deliberately OUT of the demo and are
addressed in proposal prose only.

## Scope fences (respect the caps)
- 1 hero: login -> book -> pay -> role-scoped patient + admin dashboards.
- At most 2 supporting features: (1) mocked Stripe checkout/subscription, (2) the
  admin view / role separation. Treat the audit-log panel and secure-file-upload
  affordance as lightweight set dressing inside the hero, not as additional full
  features. Do NOT build real Stripe, real Supabase, or a Next.js server.
- Demo touches <= ~12 files; build timeout 3 min; reflection retries <= 2; web
  research <= ~6 fetches.

## Constraints, risks, red flags to respect
- Named stack is the whole point. The proposal and deck must speak Next.js +
  Supabase (Auth, Postgres, RLS, Storage) + Stripe (webhooks, subscriptions) +
  Vercel + TypeScript fluently and concretely, and must be explicit that the live
  demo simulates that architecture same-origin (mw-backend as the Supabase/Stripe
  stand-in). Be honest about this so it reads as integrity, not overclaim.
- HIPAA: client says "you don't need to be a compliance expert" but DO need
  HIPAA-aware practices (least-privilege RLS, PHI minimization, audit logging,
  encrypted-at-rest framing, BAA awareness for Supabase/Stripe/Vercel). Speak to
  this with specific, practical engineering choices, not compliance buzzwords.
- This is a trust/judgment hire for a non-technical founding team. Voice should be
  practical, calm, senior: realistic estimates, sensible early-stage tradeoffs,
  "here's what I'd do first and why," willingness to suggest better approaches.
- "Do not send a generic proposal." Reference the live demo by name and link,
  reference Sesame's flow specifically, and answer their requirements concretely.

## REQUIRED application items (must ALL appear in the cover letter)
The posting lists a "To apply" checklist; every item must be addressed:
  1. A few examples of relevant projects + what Michael did on each.
  2. Experience with Next.js, Stripe, Supabase, and Vercel (name each).
  3. Any healthcare / HIPAA / privacy-related project experience.
  4. Availability.
  5. Hourly rate or rough project pricing.
And the body must start with HEALTHSTACK (see HARD GATE above). intake must turn
each of these into an explicit, checkable requirement.

## Quality + naming guidance for downstream
- intake: Extract EVERY explicit requirement into brief.json as a checklist. The
  "what we need help with" list (Next.js build, Supabase auth/db/storage/perms,
  Stripe payments/subscriptions/webhooks, Vercel deploy/manage, user dashboards +
  admin views, secure access per user type, careful healthcare data handling,
  pragmatic early-stage technical decisions, bug-fix/perf/launch readiness). The
  "looking for" list (strong Next.js/React, Supabase auth + RLS, real Stripe incl
  webhooks + subscriptions, TypeScript, production-ready features, good comms +
  realistic estimates, independence, suggests better approaches). The nice-to-haves
  (HIPAA-aware/privacy apps, appointment/scheduling, secure file upload, admin
  dashboards, Tailwind/shadcn, MVP-to-launch, startup/small-team). The "To apply"
  checklist (5 items above). Flag the HEALTHSTACK keyword as a gating requirement
  and US-healthcare market as context. Capture Michael's note ("use Next.js, React,
  and Supabase") as a confirmed stack constraint.
- planner: hero = login -> book -> Stripe-style pay -> role-scoped patient + admin
  dashboards; supporting = mock Stripe checkout/subscription and the admin/role
  separation. Greenlight the mw-backend `healthstack_blueprint.py` explicitly.
  Record lean-full. Build the requirement-to-feature traceability matrix so each
  brief.json requirement maps to demo, deck, or cover-letter prose.
- researcher: capture Sesame's flow (browse care -> book -> pay per visit or
  membership) and any specifics worth referencing; confirm the Supabase RLS +
  Stripe webhook + Vercel facts to be cited accurately; identify
  `spotify_blueprint.py` as the exact clone target. Cap at ~6 fetches.
- demo-builder: use slug `healthstack-patient-portal` for the public demo folder,
  workSamples `slug`, and route. Add `healthstack_blueprint.py` by cloning
  `spotify_blueprint.py`; register in `server.py`; keep CORS open. Seed + record
  patient and admin demo credentials. Use the site design tokens (dark gallery
  aesthetic) so the demo belongs to the site; a clean clinical/health accent is
  fine within the palette. No em/en dashes anywhere in UI copy.
- deploy / deploy-test: backend changed, so push BOTH repos; deploy-test logs in
  as both seeded roles and verifies the patient cannot see admin data and the
  pay/book flow completes. VERDICT pass before media-capture.
- proposal-writer: cover letter FIRST WORD = HEALTHSTACK; answer all 5 "To apply"
  items; embed the live demo link in cover letter AND deck; cite the role-based
  access + HIPAA-aware choices concretely; Michael's voice; no generic filler; no
  em/en dashes.
- evaluator: verify the HEALTHSTACK first-word gate, the 5 application items, the
  6 standard hard gates, and that the named stack is addressed honestly (demo
  simulates Supabase/Stripe same-origin, production = Next.js/Vercel).

